segments.text: As we talk about the talent that the College of Education has and has enjoyed and the fact that the college is attracting really top quality people in reading and in a lot of the areas.
Well, and top students too.
Sure.
Where is the motivation primarily from to get these people to really reach their highest potential if they're not already doing so?
Well, I think we have some.
I think we have a lot of outstanding people, and I think we have some people who are pretty close to reaching their potential.
I'm not sure if anybody ever reaches their full potential, but I think we have some that are doing it.
But I think that as a college, maybe not so much as individuals, but more as a college,
or as groups or as programs to gain national visibility in certain areas of research and recognition, I don't think we're reaching our potential there.
I think we're doing a good job.
I think we're recognized as a good school.
But I don't think we're reaching our potential there.
And what could you see as the solution to that dilemma?
I mean, how do you see that changing?
Well, I think if we're going to change it, I think we're going to have to set some incentives or some reasons
Why?
What would be some incentives that you think would provide the right motivation?
Well, set some goals and some program development or research goals or collaborative goals and tie it to salary increases and set some.
There have to be some incentives.
I mean, if I'm going to get my salary no matter what I do, you know, and you're on a 12-month contract, wife,
Why should I go out here and I'm going to do what I want to do because this is what I'm interested in.
And I think to a certain extent you ought to have that in a university.
But I think that we're going to have to have some, we're going to have to set some goals and I think we're going to have to develop some incentives.
Okay.
Let's talk about that for just a second because part of this organizational behavior and decision making and so forth, setting goals is the first one of any of them.
How are goals set for the College of Education?
Is it done strictly by department or is there goals for the whole deal?
Well, I think that's an area that we need to be working on to set goals and improve our planning process.
And I wouldn't say that that's so much a fault of the colleges of the university.
I think that now they're starting
with a new chancellor and everything, they're starting a planning process now.
And I think that if they do it correctly, then it could be a good experience.
There was a study a few years back called the Target 2000.
That was basically a goal-setting type project.
Have the goals that the College of Education set at that time been reached and have they been evaluated?
to see where we are compared to where the...
I'm not aware that they have, so yeah.
We talked about it at the Development Council meeting about going back to see where we are from...
I think that would be a good idea, yeah.
I think that would be a good idea.
Okay.
You've been at Texas A&M now for 17 years?
17 years.

And so I'm sure that, like everybody else, you have your own little crystal ball as to where you see there's some dramatic things coming up that are going to affect the College of Education and the legislature.
has its way and so forth.
What do you think this college is going to become?
What is going to become of the college and how will it be affected in your opinion?
Well, I'm not really sure my crystal ball is too clear right now.
One thing I'm concerned about is what's going to happen to teacher education and colleges of education in the state.
I think we still don't know what the fallout is of 994
And I'm concerned about that.
I know the dean, and I know a lot of people are.
And I think that there's a lot of uneasiness among faculty in the college right now, wondering about, you know, we're going to a five-year program.
You have this 18-hour requirement, or, you know, the undergraduate degrees and teacher education have more than 18 hours in education.
And they're still waiting for the...

coordinating board and TEA to interpret that and I think we're trying to be positive about it and that though obviously Dean Corrigan and a lot of the key people in teacher education think it's important that we go to a five-year program but there is still the possibility that the coordinating board could limit the ability of the colleges to do that.
Why will that decision be?
It's my understanding that
that some of these decisions are in the process of being made now and that we might at least have some fairly definitive information about the first part of December.
Because you have to set and plan for the classes for next year and what's going to happen.
I'm really concerned about our legislators and the image.
Obviously, our college has a good image in the state, but I'm really concerned about the image of education and colleges of education have in the state when you have
legislature passing a bill like that, it's obviously a pretty poor image.
And he pushed it, or even added to the legislation, or even interpreted that legislation very strictly, and it could put colleges and education out of business.
How did that come about?
How did that even come to the front?
Well, I think that there are people, and I think it's a misunderstanding, I think it's a problem on both parts.
I think that there are poor teacher education programs across the state.
Well, how would you define a poor teacher education program?
Well, you know, that they don't have very many quality standards and that they're very lax on the students that they let in the teacher education programs.
And the preparation there isn't a lot, in terms of especially the education courses, there isn't a lot of substance to the courses.
You've heard the Mickey Mouse education courses and things of this nature.
And there are programs like that.
So I think that's one thing that has contributed to it.
I think the other thing that has contributed to it is a lack of information or being unwilling to listen.
Because in current teacher education programs, students aren't taking a lot of hours in education anyway.

subject matter courses and there's a lot and we need to communicate and I guess as educators we don't communicate very well but there's a lot more to teaching than just knowing the subject matter I think you have to really know the subject matter and you have to be in courses that are very demanding but I also think there's a there's a methodology there's a pedagogy there's information relating to understanding kids you know growth and development and the whole thing testing there's all this and

and so i think there's a misconceptions on both i think there's some poor programs that need to be cleaned up and i think also that the legislature and the public isn't aware we need to tell our story a little better that's right that's right that's right so i don't know i think that uh i'm concerned i'm concerned about what uh what the future might hold now i've been a teacher and a

high school counselor before I came to A&M, and I have about 12 years of public school experience, so I have quite a bit of public school experience, although it's been a few years since I've been out there.
But I'm not a teacher educator.
I mean, I have the public school experience, but I'm not a teacher educator.
My area is counseling, and so I'm very interested in teacher education, and I've had the public school experience, but I am not a teacher educator.
Some of these things I'm kind of looking at and I'm involved and I'm concerned about them, but some of them I'm not intimately involved in.
Now let's look a little bit about what you feel in your years at A&M.
You have contributed

in your own special way, or maybe even through some of the insights or observations that you've made, and everybody's reluctant to talk about what they've done, and somebody said, well, you need to find that out from somebody else.
Let them say what I have done.
But what do you feel the best about, since you've been at A&M, that you've been involved in?
Well, for a number of years, I came out of soft money position, and I was very involved in funded research and
about 70s or about 78 when I became department head and didn't have really the time to concentrate on that anymore.
I had a funded research project every year or sometimes several of them.
So that was exciting and I enjoyed that.

So I would say that I was probably one of the people early on in the college, not the only one because there were a lot of others, but I was one of those who was out there trying to get external funds.
I would say another thing that I would, in terms of department heads, and what I did when I was a department head, is the APA accreditation in the Ed Psych department for Conacyt Psych.
They had been talking about it for a number of years and saying, well, we're going to get a self-study together, we're going to bring in a consultant.
And one of my main goals was to quit talking about
And to me, I don't take the full credit for it, but in terms of leadership, I do.
APA accreditation is the?
American Psychological Association.
And that's a very key, very selective type thing.
When was that?
The first APA accreditation for the counseling psych program was in 1980.
And does that have to be renewable every?
Every five years.

And the other thing that I really liked about it, that I think the faculty and students, everybody was pleased about, is usually when you go up for accreditation the first time, you don't get full accreditation.
You usually get three years and probationary, or conditional, I think it's conditional.
And we got full five years and full accreditation the first time.
lots of major universities across the country that didn't get that.
So that was very pleasing to me.
And then also, I think, before I stepped out of the department head's position, I think that I had helped set the groundwork for moving towards accreditation for a school site.
And I guess the other thing, too, that I tried to do as a department head was to
cut back on the faculty load to get faculty more time to do research and work with students, and cut back on the number of courses that they teach.
What is the average, and what's too much?
Well, in terms of graduate courses, two graduate courses.
Is about average?
Right.
In ed psych.
It is in some of the other, but in ed psych.
What size classes are they usually?
Well, graduate courses usually run 10 to 15 students apiece.
And are there any special insights or anecdotes or things?
One of the things that you're doing now in this position is working with the Development Council as part of your office.
I only have one other person that's been involved in the Development Council, and that's Don Clark, who was in your position when this thing got started.
Can you give me just a little bit of a couple of insights about your association with the Development Council and what you think
that particular entity is doing or should do or has done to assist the College of Education in any way?
Well, I think the role of the Development Council is changing.
I think initially it was put together more as an advisory group, and I think that there's more pressure to go after funding.
And it isn't all from the college.
I think some of it's coming external to the college, like from the
provost's office and the president's office, and there's a lot of competitiveness there.
And so I think that the role of the development council is changing.
But it has given me an opportunity to meet someand I'm notyou are, but I don't meanI'm notbut to meet some real fine people.
I don't want to sound patronizing.
No, no.
But it has.
It has given me an opportunity to meet a lot of really fine people and interesting people.

and get involved in meeting a lot of former students and people in business and industry that, you know, as a faculty member you would typically, or even as an administrator, you might not have as much of an opportunity to meet.
Okay, now that you mention this, as an administrator, can you just give me a little bit of insight into the eighth floor of the College of Education?
I visit up there frequently, but what is the mechanism

You know, I know it's a huge organization, and there's a lot of decision-making, but I don't have a feel as an outsider, and not having worked, I've never been to a faculty meeting, I don't know what is the decision-making process, and what actually happens up there as it affects the whole college.
Well, there are two different levels, or I mean, maybe the same level, but there's a dean and his staff, and...
it would consist of two associate deans, Brian Cohen, myself, and David Davis, assistant dean, and then our business person, Larry Dooling.

And we meet maybe not every Monday in case some of us are out of town, but we usually meet every Monday morning with the dean to go through our calendars and just go through different things that are coming up that week or in the future.
And then we also, each of us have
bi-weekly meetings with the dean in about an hour to kind of go through and discuss things individually.
And we have special meetings from time to time.
Then the other process, decision-making process and direction, we have what we call a policy committee, which consists of all the department heads and the dean staff, and it's chaired by the dean.
And that meets the first Tuesday, the first and third Tuesday of every month.
And occasionally there's a call meeting, but that's when that meets.
I would say that a lot of the, that's where the decision making and whole process evolves.
In Corrigan, there's a lot more participation and more of a democratic type leadership.
There certainly is a very distinct difference between the two styles.
Is there a lot of autonomy?

I want to say that the different associate deans and the different people on the eighth floor, as far as everybody having very specific deals, are you responsible for certain areas only and though the decisions come directly from you or directly from Brian Cole or directly from David David or whoever is in that position?
The dean likes to give us, to run our, I mean we're staff people.
But he likes to, we have certain responsibilities.
So for example, can you just give me some of the things, I know the development council is one of yours.
What are some of the other things of your particular?
Well, development council, development, external funding, all proposals, any funding opportunities, all that goes through my office.
Graduate studies goes through my office.
So I'm chair of the
College Graduate Instruction Committee, which I represent from each department, and all new course proposals or anything related to graduate study goes through my office.
And then since I'm chair of the College Graduate Instruction Committee, I'm also a member of the University Graduate Council.
Which does what?
It reviews all new course proposals and anything relating to graduate study.
And do those course proposals come from the department heads to you first?
Can I take them to the graduate instruction committee in the college or review them?
And then if we pass on them, we might ask them to change a little bit, and then it's in accordance with our recommendation, and he sends it out to the graduate office.
There was a comment made about the fact that, of course, the funding to the College of Education comes from courses and from student hours.
That's what generates the largest amount of funds.
Is that correct?

And that a lot of times, we're trying to get more courses so that I can teach more students, so that we can, in other words, the expression was something about we can become a dinosaur, just trying to add more courses so that we can have more classes.
Is that a different type of perception?
Well, I think some departments and some programs, I think we have to look at the number of students and the number of things we're doing and the areas that we're trying to do too much.
By trying to do too much .
Well, for instance, we have a large graduate program in the college.
I'm just talking about the specific department.
And I think for the number of faculty that some departments have, they've just taken on too many graduate students.
And I think that to do an adequate job, they need to cut back.
I mean, for instance, I think the graduate courses, I think an ideal size to really interact
do research and write courses and have the dialogue that you need, I think should be, at the most, 10 to 15 students.
And I mean, there are graduate courses that are a lot larger than that.
And I really question that in terms of that.
Yeah.
I mean, then, because it's growing so and there's so much more demand for these courses, is there a need to just get more faculty?
Well.
That's one way you can go, but you can also get so big that the thing gets kind of unwielding.
Plus, I don't think the chances are real good now with the economic conditions that we have in the state and the funding that we have.
I don't think the conditions are good that we're going to get a lot more faculty.
I really think that what we need to do is be looking at quality.
And I'm not saying we don't have quality, but I think we need to be cutting back in some areas.
shouldn't be chairing more than four or five doctoral students apiece.
And I felt that for a long time, and I think that we need to come back there.
And who makes those kinds of decisions?
Like, do you feel like some faculty would Well, the individual departments and faculty do.
And we came acrosswe came out with it.
We had a joint committee of our graduate instruction committee and steering committee on inquiry that developed a paper, and we had input from faculty and students.
It's calledI think it's How to Improve Doctoral Research or something.
And there's a whole set of recommendations in there, and one of them is to cut back on the number of students we have in terms of graduates.
Oh, you're talking about the College of Education following the Texas A&M cap?
Well, maybe not quite that same way, but yeah.
Okay, one of the things though, doesn't graduate hours generate a tremendous amount of money?
But that's something that has changed quite a bit.
In the 70s, the budget that we got, they were looking at it.
They would look at the central administration and the dean's office would look at how many credit hours you generated.
There isn't that pressure to do that anymore.
Is that right?
What changed that?
I'm not sure, Sylvia.
In our own college, it's just that we matured a little bit and we didn't worry about it that much anymore.
Plus, I think the central administration just quit.
Very good.
Dr. Borman, I thank you very, very much for this interview, and I believe that you've given me some very valuable insights on the administrative end.
This is my first administration interview.
